This dataset (the "CCTV-SPCrime" dataset, including images, annotations, and
documentation produced by the authors) is licensed under the

  Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License (CC BY 4.0):

- Human-readable summary: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0
- Full legal code:        https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/legalcode

You are free to share and adapt the material for any purpose, even commercially,
provided you give appropriate credit, provide a link to the license, and indicate
if changes were made.

How to attribute
----------------

Please cite the dataset using the data paper (see CITATION.cff):

    Pena, S. B. N.; Souza, J. R.; Nomura, S. (2026). CCTV-SPCrime: a dataset and
    an event-oriented annotation policy for public-safety incident detection in
    surveillance images. [venue/DOI to be filled].

Third-party components and provenance
-------------------------------------

This dataset aggregates material from multiple sources. Components incorporated
from third parties REMAIN under their original licenses; the per-sample
provenance and license of every item are recorded in `provenance/`:

- Components released under CC0 / public domain or permissive licenses
    (e.g., MIT) are redistributed here under their original terms.
- Components released under CC BY require attribution to their original
    authors (recorded in `provenance/`).
- Sources with non-derivative (ND) or non-commercial-incompatible terms,
    or whose redistribution rights are unclear, were EXCLUDED from this dataset
    (used, if at all, only as external benchmarks — see the project documentation).

Why CC BY 4.0 (and not CC0)
---------------------------

Because the dataset includes components licensed under CC BY (which require
attribution), the aggregate is released under CC BY 4.0 for license
compatibility: CC0 would be appropriate ONLY if every included component were
CC0, public domain, or authored solely by the dataset creators. If you build a
variant restricted exclusively to CC0/public-domain/own data, you may instead
release that variant under CC0 1.0 (SPDX: CC0-1.0).
